{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01R1NRfSiTTUEVoLFX6YJK6U","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The application started successfully but there are two issues:\n\n1. **Jackson UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE issue**: The `ObjectMapperCustomizer` is enabling `UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE` on the Quarkus default ObjectMapper used by RESTEasy for deserialization. This means when the body `{\"user\": {...}}` comes in, Jackson treats `\"user\"` as a root name and tries to unwrap it - but `NewUserRequestWrapper` doesn't have `@JsonRootName(\"NewUserRequestWrapper\")` matching that root. The wrapper classes already have a `user` field, so we shouldn't be unwrapping on deserialization.\n\n2. **Tags response missing 'tags' key**: The tags endpoint returns wrapped JSON (because of WRAP_ROOT_VALUE), but the response model for tags probably doesn't have `@JsonRootName`.\n\nThe root cause: The original app used manual `objectMapper.writeValueAsString()` for serialization (so WRAP_ROOT_VALUE was fine for outgoing responses), but RESTEasy's deserialization also uses the same ObjectMapper now. We need to NOT enable UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE on the global ObjectMapper - only use it when explicitly serializing.\n\nThe fix: Don't customize the Quarkus ObjectMapper. Instead, keep the original CDI producer approach but use `@io.quarkus.arc.DefaultBean` or `@Alternative` to avoid conflicts. Actually the better approach is to NOT customize the global ObjectMapper at all, and only have the two custom producers injected where needed.\n\nLet me also check the request wrapper models:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2560,"cache_read_input_tokens":90264,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2560,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":598},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d54d9ac2-22a6-4fd0-85db-0f21ac49e7c7","uuid":"8d409523-ba46-4c78-afc7-846a5e38e802"}
