{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01VZeXcgDkXiE8SMc4YJyaAT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_bdrk_01AnRMfwWqdCAy4HSsioz1F2","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__realworld__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/example/realworldapi/application/web/resource/TagsResource.java"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1578,"cache_read_input_tokens":92824,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1578,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":149},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d54d9ac2-22a6-4fd0-85db-0f21ac49e7c7","uuid":"b24f95b9-cf66-49df-842e-705344ef8f98"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01AnRMfwWqdCAy4HSsioz1F2","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.application.web.resource;\n     2→\n     3→import jakarta.inject.Inject;\n     4→import jakarta.ws.rs.GET;\n     5→import jakarta.ws.rs.Path;\n     6→import jakarta.ws.rs.Produces;\n     7→import jakarta.ws.rs.core.MediaType;\n     8→import jakarta.ws.rs.core.Response;\n     9→import org.example.realworldapi.application.web.model.response.TagsResponse;\n    10→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.FindTags;\n    11→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.tag.Tag;\n    12→\n    13→import java.util.List;\n    14→\n    15→@Path(\"/tags\")\n    16→public class TagsResource {\n    17→\n    18→    @Inject\n    19→    private FindTags findTags;\n    20→\n    21→    @GET\n    22→    @Produces(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)\n    23→    public Response getTags() {\n    24→        List<Tag> tags = findTags.handle();\n    25→        return Response.ok(new TagsResponse(tags))\n    26→                .status(Response.Status.OK)\n    27→                .build();\n    28→    }\n    29→}\n    30→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d54d9ac2-22a6-4fd0-85db-0f21ac49e7c7","uuid":"e71977a3-0907-4933-b9c8-f305ffd801bf"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_012nebuhsARJ8r9AVYDqQrWH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I see the full picture. The `TagsResource.getTags()` returns `Response.ok(new TagsResponse(tags))` - it passes the object directly to `Response.ok()`, NOT using `objectMapper.writeValueAsString()`. So RESTEasy/Jackson serializes this object. With WRAP_ROOT_VALUE enabled globally, it would wrap it as `{\"TagsResponse\": {\"tags\": [...]}}` instead of `{\"tags\": [...]}`.\n\nThe fundamental issue is: The original app used two patterns:\n1. Resource methods that manually serialize with `objectMapper.writeValueAsString()` - these use the custom ObjectMapper with WRAP_ROOT_VALUE (for `@JsonRootName` objects like UserResponse, ArticleResponse)\n2. Resource methods that pass objects directly to `Response.ok(object)` - these rely on RESTEasy's ObjectMapper, which should NOT have WRAP_ROOT_VALUE\n\n**Solution**: The Quarkus global ObjectMapper (used by RESTEasy for both serialization and deserialization) should NOT have WRAP_ROOT_VALUE/UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE. Only the explicitly injected ObjectMapper beans should have those settings. So we need to revert the SerializerConfig to produce two separate ObjectMapper beans without modifying the global one.\n\nThe trick is avoiding ambiguity with Quarkus's default ObjectMapper. We can use `@Named` or `@io.quarkus.arc.Unremovable` with an `@Alternative` with priority. Actually, the cleanest approach in Quarkus is to use `@io.quarkus.arc.DefaultBean` on the Quarkus side, or to not produce an unqualified ObjectMapper and instead inject it with a custom qualifier.\n\nLooking at how the code injects ObjectMapper:\n- `ArticlesResource` injects `ObjectMapper objectMapper` (unqualified) and `@NoWrapRootValueObjectMapper ObjectMapper noWrapObjectMapper`\n- `UsersResource` injects `ObjectMapper objectMapper` (unqualified)\n- `BusinessExceptionMapper` injects `ObjectMapper objectMapper` (unqualified)\n\nThese need the WRAP_ROOT_VALUE ObjectMapper. But RESTEasy also uses the default unqualified ObjectMapper. \n\nThe solution: Don't use a CDI producer for the unqualified ObjectMapper. Instead, use a named/qualified bean for the WRAP_ROOT_VALUE version, and update injection points."}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":589,"cache_read_input_tokens":94402,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":589,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1110},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d54d9ac2-22a6-4fd0-85db-0f21ac49e7c7","uuid":"4790312f-c5f2-4893-93cb-e73defacd1fb"}
