{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_015NTdc54AVhwgHSqpM3Y6YX","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.application.web.model.response;\n     2→\n     3→import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonRootName;\n     4→import lombok.Getter;\n     5→import lombok.Setter;\n     6→\n     7→import java.util.LinkedList;\n     8→import java.util.List;\n     9→\n    10→@Getter\n    11→@Setter\n    12→@JsonRootName(\"errors\")\n    13→public class ErrorResponse {\n    14→\n    15→    private List<String> body;\n    16→\n    17→    public ErrorResponse() {\n    18→        this.body = new LinkedList<>();\n    19→    }\n    20→\n    21→    public ErrorResponse(String error) {\n    22→        this();\n    23→        this.body.add(error);\n    24→    }\n    25→\n    26→    public ErrorResponse(List<String> errors) {\n    27→        this.body = errors;\n    28→    }\n    29→}\n    30→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d54d9ac2-22a6-4fd0-85db-0f21ac49e7c7","uuid":"7450ce9a-4b57-48ad-8d96-84a5b0fac3b5"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01V67RardmaVnLDDTra54etL","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.application.web.model.response;\n     2→\n     3→import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonRootName;\n     4→import lombok.Getter;\n     5→import lombok.Setter;\n     6→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.user.User;\n     7→\n     8→@Getter\n     9→@Setter\n    10→@JsonRootName(\"profile\")\n    11→public class ProfileResponse {\n    12→\n    13→    private String username;\n    14→    private String bio;\n    15→    private String image;\n    16→    private boolean following;\n    17→\n    18→    public ProfileResponse(User user) {\n    19→        this.username = user.getUsername();\n    20→        this.bio = user.getBio();\n    21→        this.image = user.getImage();\n    22→    }\n    23→}\n    24→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d54d9ac2-22a6-4fd0-85db-0f21ac49e7c7","uuid":"2b4bbacc-679f-401f-aaac-656a4e591ebc"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01UmhXaaowHRASzF1zXhVZtA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I understand the full design pattern:\n\n- Response models with `@JsonRootName`: `UserResponse(\"user\")`, `ArticleResponse(\"article\")`, `ErrorResponse(\"errors\")`, `ProfileResponse(\"profile\")`\n- These are serialized manually using `objectMapper.writeValueAsString()` with WRAP_ROOT_VALUE enabled, producing `{\"user\": {...}}`, `{\"article\": {...}}`, etc.\n- The `noWrapObjectMapper` is used for list responses (`ArticlesResponse`, `CommentsResponse`) that don't need wrapping\n- `TagsResponse` has no `@JsonRootName` but `TagsResource.getTags()` passes the object directly to `Response.ok()` (not using writeValueAsString). So RESTEasy's Jackson MessageBodyWriter serializes it. With WRAP_ROOT_VALUE, it wraps as `{\"TagsResponse\": {\"tags\": [...]}}` instead of `{\"tags\": [...]}`.\n\n**The correct fix**: The Quarkus ObjectMapper (used by RESTEasy) should NOT have WRAP_ROOT_VALUE. We need two separate custom ObjectMapper instances, both with custom qualifiers. The unqualified injection (default ObjectMapper) from Quarkus is fine for RESTEasy deserialization/serialization.\n\nLet me create a new qualifier and update all the injection points:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1373,"cache_read_input_tokens":101448,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1373,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":438},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d54d9ac2-22a6-4fd0-85db-0f21ac49e7c7","uuid":"10ec2f69-95f0-4fa3-bfec-cae3627675e6"}
